   {:e #blake3 "9b530cc2e32f0a48a0b495e41f957870d273bcafb115c264030bfd3c248c18ec" :a :spec/source-file :v "03-query.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "9b530cc2e32f0a48a0b495e41f957870d273bcafb115c264030bfd3c248c18ec" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS SQ-004\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`\n**Stage**: 2\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\nEigenvector centrality is the dominant eigenvector of the adjacency matrix A:\n\nA × x = λ × x, where λ is the largest eigenvalue\n\nEC(v) = x_v / max(x)\n\nProperties:\n  1. Non-negative (Perron-Frobenius for non-negative matrices)\n  2. Recursive influence: high EC ⟹ connected to other high-EC vertices\n  3. Convergence: power iteration converges for connected graphs\n  4. Relationship to PageRank: PageRank ≈ damped eigenvector centrality\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nEigenvector centrality is a Stratum 1 query. It provides refined authority\nscoring beyond PageRank by capturing recursive influence without damping.\nAvailable at Stage 2 when branch-level analysis makes refined scoring valuable.\n\n#### Level 2 (Implementation Contract)\n```rust\npub fn eigenvector_centrality(\n    store: &Store,\n    entity_type: &Attribute,\n    dep_attr: &Attribute,\n    epsilon: f64,         // convergence: 1e-6\n    max_iterations: u32,  // safety: 100\n) -> Vec<(EntityId, f64)> {\n    // Power iteration on adjacency matrix: O(iterations × (V + E))\n}\n```\n\n**Falsification**: Any centrality score is negative (Perron-Frobenius violation),\nOR scores are not normalized to [0, 1], OR the same graph produces\ndifferent centrality rankings across invocations.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "9b530cc2e32f0a48a0b495e41f957870d273bcafb115c264030bfd3c248c18ec" :a :spec/statement :v "``` Eigenvector centrality is the dominant eigenvector of the adjacency matrix A: A × x = λ × x, where λ is the largest eigenvalue EC(v) = x_v / max(x) Properties: 1. Non-negative (Perron-Frobenius for non-negative matrices) 2. Recursive influence: high EC ⟹ connected to other high-EC vertices 3. Convergence: power iteration converges for connected graphs 4. Relationship to PageRank: PageRank ≈ damped eigenvector centrality ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "9b530cc2e32f0a48a0b495e41f957870d273bcafb115c264030bfd3c248c18ec" :a :spec/falsification :v "Any centrality score is negative (Perron-Frobenius violation), OR scores are not normalized to [0, 1], OR the same graph produces different centrality rankings across invocations." :op :assert}
