   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :db/doc :v "Six-Stratum Classification" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :spec/source-file :v "03-query.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS SQ-004, SQ-009\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nHow to organize query patterns by safety and cost?\n\n#### Decision\nSix strata: Stratum 0 (primitive, monotonic), Stratum 1 (graph traversal, monotonic),\nStratum 2 (uncertainty, mixed), Stratum 3 (authority, FFI), Stratum 4 (conflict detection,\nconservatively monotonic), Stratum 5 (bilateral loop, non-monotonic).\n\nThe classification enables systematic safety analysis: Strata 0–1 are always safe.\nStratum 4 is safe but conservative (may overcount). Strata 2–3 and 5 require specific\nfrontier or barrier guarantees.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS SQ-004, SQ-009" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :adr/problem :v "How to organize query patterns by safety and cost?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "409306fed9009f6013098de2b6fa84d64b08b87471fbc185db9bc2da1f7cdc2c" :a :adr/decision :v "Six strata: Stratum 0 (primitive, monotonic), Stratum 1 (graph traversal, monotonic), Stratum 2 (uncertainty, mixed), Stratum 3 (authority, FFI), Stratum 4 (conflict detection, conservatively monotonic), Stratum 5 (bilateral loop, non-monotonic). The classification enables systematic safety analysis: Strata 0–1 are always safe. Stratum 4 is safe but conservative (may overcount). Strata 2–3 and 5 require specific frontier or barrier guarantees." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-query-004 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/query :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :db/doc :v "FFI for Derived Functions" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :spec/source-file :v "03-query.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS SQ-010\n**Stage**: 1\n\n#### Problem\nThree core computations cannot be expressed in pure Datalog: σ_a (entropy), σ_c (DAG\ntraversal with memoization), spectral authority (SVD). How to handle this?\n\n#### Options\nA) **Extend Datalog** — add aggregation, recursion, linear algebra to the query language.\nB) **FFI mechanism** — Datalog provides input data; Rust function computes result.\nC) **Out-of-band computation** — separate process computes, results stored as datoms.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option B.** The FFI boundary cleanly separates declarative queries (Datalog's strength)\nfrom imperative computation (Rust's strength). The derived function is pure — same inputs,\nsame output.\n\n#### Formal Justification\nMajor architectural implication: three of four core coordination computations (σ_a, σ_c,\nspectral authority) are derived functions. Option A would bloat the query language beyond\nDatalog's well-understood theoretical properties. Option B preserves Datalog's properties\nwhile enabling necessary computation.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS SQ-010" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :adr/problem :v "Three core computations cannot be expressed in pure Datalog: σ_a (entropy), σ_c (DAG traversal with memoization), spectral authority (SVD). How to handle this?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "4d11833a52b78231b1c795be9f11e47267678b4d431951ae37d451e769a75336" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option B.** The FFI boundary cleanly separates declarative queries (Datalog's strength) from imperative computation (Rust's strength). The derived function is pure — same inputs, same output." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a65992449ae507b0b37d20e56a90748b01ffcce01acfaa748d12002a6e7dba9" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-query-005 :op :assert}
