   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :db/doc :v "Per-Attribute Resolution" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: SEED §4 Axiom 5, ADRS FD-005\n**Verification**: `V:TYPE`, `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\n∀ attributes a: ∃ resolution_mode(a) ∈ {LWW, Lattice, Multi}\n  (every attribute declares its conflict resolution strategy)\n\nresolution_mode is an attribute of the attribute entity:\n  (attr_entity, :db/resolutionMode, mode, tx, Assert)\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nNo attribute exists without a declared resolution mode. The default (if not explicitly\nset) is LWW with HLC clock.\n\n#### Level 2 (Implementation Contract)\n```rust\nimpl Schema {\n    pub fn resolution_mode(&self, attr: &Attribute) -> ResolutionMode {\n        self.attribute(attr)\n            .and_then(|def| def.resolution_mode)\n            .unwrap_or(ResolutionMode::LastWriterWins)\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Falsification**: A conflict arising on an attribute with no defined resolution mode\nand no default applied.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :spec/statement :v "``` ∀ attributes a: ∃ resolution_mode(a) ∈ {LWW, Lattice, Multi} (every attribute declares its conflict resolution strategy) resolution_mode is an attribute of the attribute entity: (attr_entity, :db/resolutionMode, mode, tx, Assert) ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :spec/falsification :v "A conflict arising on an attribute with no defined resolution mode and no default applied." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :element/traces-to :v "SEED §4 Axiom 5, ADRS FD-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2162930573da18f01f78c3d4a02db7a7f6a5ff1e07c337beb8477432548f2b9c" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:TYPE`, `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-002 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :db/doc :v "Resolution Commutativity" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS AS-001, FD-005\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\n∀ resolution modes M, ∀ value sets V₁, V₂:\n  M.resolve(V₁ ∪ V₂) = M.resolve(V₂ ∪ V₁)\n  (resolution is order-independent — critical for CRDT consistency)\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nTwo agents independently resolving the same conflict arrive at the same value,\nregardless of the order in which they receive the conflicting datoms.\n\n**Falsification**: Two agents with the same datom set producing different resolved\nvalues for the same entity-attribute pair.\n\n**proptest strategy**: Generate random sets of conflicting values, resolve in all\npermutations, assert identical results.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/statement :v "``` ∀ resolution modes M, ∀ value sets V₁, V₂: M.resolve(V₁ ∪ V₂) = M.resolve(V₂ ∪ V₁) (resolution is order-independent — critical for CRDT consistency) ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/falsification :v "Two agents with the same datom set producing different resolved values for the same entity-attribute pair." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS AS-001, FD-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "518a935d0614f605a2a9b072c1e9a6a28b7c22789a3d2909cb0794b24664fece" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-003 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :db/doc :v "Conservative Conflict Detection" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-001\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:MODEL`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\n∀ frontiers F_local, F_global where F_local ⊆ F_global:\n  conflicts(F_local) ⊇ conflicts(F_global)\n  (local frontier overestimates conflicts — no false negatives)\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nAn agent at a local frontier may see phantom conflicts (safe — wasted effort).\nIt MUST NOT miss real conflicts (critical — silent data corruption).\n\n**Falsification**: A real conflict at the global frontier that is not detected at\nsome agent's local frontier that has received both conflicting datoms.\n\n**Stateright model**: Model 3 agents independently transacting conflicting values.\nVerify that every merge detects all conflicts, even with partial frontier views.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/statement :v "``` ∀ frontiers F_local, F_global where F_local ⊆ F_global: conflicts(F_local) ⊇ conflicts(F_global) (local frontier overestimates conflicts — no false negatives) ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/falsification :v "A real conflict at the global frontier that is not detected at some agent's local frontier that has received both conflicting datoms." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-001" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "b0f850e9e2a2a79e0afcf7893cc648eb8b377880511ecd3840820c1f3adc350c" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:MODEL`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-004 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :db/doc :v "Conflict Predicate Correctness" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-006\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\nconflict(d₁, d₂) ⟺\n  same_entity(d₁, d₂) ∧ same_attribute(d₁, d₂) ∧\n  different_value(d₁, d₂) ∧ both_assert(d₁, d₂) ∧\n  cardinality_one(d₁.a) ∧ causally_independent(d₁.tx, d₂.tx)\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nThe conflict predicate requires ALL six conditions. Missing any condition\neither misses real conflicts or flags non-conflicts:\n- Without causal independence check: updates falsely flagged as conflicts\n- Without cardinality check: multi-value attributes falsely flagged\n- Without same-entity check: unrelated datoms falsely paired\n\n**Falsification**: A pair of datoms satisfying all six conditions not flagged as conflict,\nor a pair violating any condition that IS flagged.\n\n**proptest strategy**: Generate datom pairs with systematic variation of each condition.\nVerify conflict predicate matches expected boolean.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/statement :v "``` conflict(d₁, d₂) ⟺ same_entity(d₁, d₂) ∧ same_attribute(d₁, d₂) ∧ different_value(d₁, d₂) ∧ both_assert(d₁, d₂) ∧ cardinality_one(d₁.a) ∧ causally_independent(d₁.tx, d₂.tx) ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/falsification :v "A pair of datoms satisfying all six conditions not flagged as conflict, or a pair violating any condition that IS flagged." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-006" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1a530b0c510be8fd8bf393c7b2b39dbe2b24ba137e0b32bdb01078b78e9b4e6c" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-005 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :db/doc :v "LWW Semilattice Properties" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS FD-005\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\nFor LWW resolution with clock C:\n  Commutativity: lww(v₁, v₂) = lww(v₂, v₁)\n  Associativity: lww(lww(v₁, v₂), v₃) = lww(v₁, lww(v₂, v₃))\n  Idempotency:   lww(v, v) = v\n\nTie-breaking (equal clock values):\n  When C(d₁) = C(d₂), the winner is the datom whose BLAKE3 hash is\n  lexicographically greater: lww(d₁, d₂) = d where blake3(d) = max(blake3(d₁), blake3(d₂)).\n  This preserves commutativity and associativity because byte comparison is a total order.\n  See ADR-RESOLUTION-009.\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nLWW picks the value with the highest clock value. When two concurrent assertions\nhave identical HLC timestamps, the tie is broken by BLAKE3 hash comparison of the\ndatom content (ADR-RESOLUTION-009). This is deterministic and topology-agnostic:\nboth agents independently compute the same winner without coordination.\n\n**Falsification**: Two agents resolving the same LWW conflict to different values,\nincluding when the conflicting datoms have identical HLC timestamps.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/statement :v "``` For LWW resolution with clock C: Commutativity: lww(v₁, v₂) = lww(v₂, v₁) Associativity: lww(lww(v₁, v₂), v₃) = lww(v₁, lww(v₂, v₃)) Idempotency:   lww(v, v) = v Tie-breaking (equal clock values): When C(d₁) = C(d₂), the winner is the datom whose BLAKE3 hash is lexicographically greater: lww(d₁, d₂) = d where blake3(d) = max(blake3(d₁), blake3(d₂)). This preserves commutativity and associativity because byte comparison is a total order. See ADR-RESOLUTION-009. ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/falsification :v "Two agents resolving the same LWW conflict to different values, including when the conflicting datoms have identical HLC timestamps." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS FD-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f38b21188a6e5835a21ee88b06375eb55113fd26613fbad55c8da973a1772bb7" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-006 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :db/doc :v "Lattice Join Correctness" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS SR-010, FD-005\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\nFor lattice resolution with lattice L:\n  join_L(v₁, v₂) ≥ v₁ AND join_L(v₁, v₂) ≥ v₂    — upper bound\n  ∀ u: u ≥ v₁ ∧ u ≥ v₂ ⟹ u ≥ join_L(v₁, v₂)       — least upper bound\n  join_L(v₁, v₂) = join_L(v₂, v₁)                   — commutativity\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nThe lattice join produces the least upper bound of the competing values.\nFor diamond lattices (INV-SCHEMA-008), the join of two incomparable elements\nproduces the error signal element.\n\n**Falsification**: A lattice join that is not the least upper bound, or\nincomparable values in a diamond lattice that don't produce the error signal.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/statement :v "``` For lattice resolution with lattice L: join_L(v₁, v₂) ≥ v₁ AND join_L(v₁, v₂) ≥ v₂    — upper bound ∀ u: u ≥ v₁ ∧ u ≥ v₂ ⟹ u ≥ join_L(v₁, v₂)       — least upper bound join_L(v₁, v₂) = join_L(v₂, v₁)                   — commutativity ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/falsification :v "A lattice join that is not the least upper bound, or incomparable values in a diamond lattice that don't produce the error signal." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS SR-010, FD-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "bfcddce912b19009d5e0a154c1b850f8822ac813cf96aa2d2383d196b196523f" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-007 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :db/doc :v "Three-Tier Routing Completeness" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-002\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`, `V:KANI`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\n∀ detected conflicts C:\n  C is routed to exactly one of {Automatic, AgentNotification, HumanRequired}\n  No conflict remains unrouted.\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nEvery detected conflict has a severity and a routing tier. The routing is total\n(all conflicts are routed) and deterministic (same severity → same tier).\n\n**Falsification**: A conflict that is detected but not routed to any tier.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/statement :v "``` ∀ detected conflicts C: C is routed to exactly one of {Automatic, AgentNotification, HumanRequired} No conflict remains unrouted. ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/falsification :v "A conflict that is detected but not routed to any tier." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-002" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d34bc12999b9d31e9f95f97ebe3d3befed7a33f066ab186f4f48f38c9d8e7a5b" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`, `V:KANI`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :db/ident :v :spec/inv-resolution-008 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/invariant :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :db/doc :v "Conflict Entity Datom Trail" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-003\n**Verification**: `V:PROP`\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Level 0 (Algebraic Law)\n```\n∀ conflict detections:\n  Steps (1) assert Conflict entity, (2) compute severity, (3) route,\n  (4) fire TUI, (5) update uncertainty, (6) invalidate caches\n  ALL produce datoms in the store.\n```\n\n#### Level 1 (State Invariant)\nThe full conflict lifecycle is recorded as datoms, making it queryable\nand auditable.\n\n**Falsification**: Any step in the conflict pipeline that does not produce a datom.\n\n**Stage 0 simplification**: At Stage 0, multi-agent conflicts are rare (single agent\nonly). Steps (1)-(3) are fully implemented: assert Conflict entity, compute severity,\nroute to resolution tier. Steps (4)-(6) produce stub datoms recording that the step\nran but performing no work: (4) TUI notification is deferred to Stage 4 (TUI layer),\n(5) uncertainty update is deferred to Stage 1 (uncertainty tensor requires BUDGET),\n(6) cache invalidation is deferred to Stage 1 (caching is an optimization). The L0\ninvariant holds — all 6 steps produce datoms — but steps 4-6 produce metadata-only\ndatoms at Stage 0. Full behavior activates progressively: Stage 1 adds (5)+(6),\nStage 4 adds (4).\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/statement :v "``` ∀ conflict detections: Steps (1) assert Conflict entity, (2) compute severity, (3) route, (4) fire TUI, (5) update uncertainty, (6) invalidate caches ALL produce datoms in the store. ```" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/falsification :v "Any step in the conflict pipeline that does not produce a datom." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-003" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "0a8e232a8d5a4fb8c3929e0a3299c26b82b246b9b333c9baeb753daa5830468e" :a :spec/verification :v "`V:PROP`" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-001 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :db/doc :v "Per-Attribute Over Global Policy" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: SEED §4 Axiom 5, §11, ADRS FD-005\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nShould conflict resolution be per-attribute or global?\n\n#### Options\nA) **Per-attribute** — each attribute declares its resolution mode (LWW, lattice, multi).\nB) **Global policy** — one resolution strategy for all attributes.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option A.** Different attributes have different semantics. Task status has a natural\nlattice (`todo < in-progress < done`). Person names do not. Forcing one resolution\npolicy on all attributes either loses information or produces nonsense.\n\n#### Formal Justification\nPer-attribute resolution preserves the semilattice property at the attribute level.\nGlobal LWW would lose lattice semantics for status-like attributes. Global lattice\nwould require defining a lattice for every attribute, including those with no natural order.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :element/traces-to :v "SEED §4 Axiom 5, §11, ADRS FD-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :adr/problem :v "Should conflict resolution be per-attribute or global?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "15bca6b00fc804dd65255f5244a886ca7fbc0a29b2a6fbcbdb3de1a056bfbea7" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option A.** Different attributes have different semantics. Task status has a natural lattice (`todo < in-progress < done`). Person names do not. Forcing one resolution policy on all attributes either loses information or produces nonsense." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-002 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :db/doc :v "Resolution at Query Time, Not Merge Time" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: C4, ADRS AS-001\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nWhen does conflict resolution happen?\n\n#### Options\nA) **At merge time** — resolve conflicts during MERGE operation.\nB) **At query time** — MERGE is pure set union; resolution happens in the LIVE index.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option B.** MERGE must be pure set union (C4). Conflict resolution at merge time\nwould make MERGE depend on schema and resolution mode, breaking the algebraic\nproperties (L1–L3 assume set union).\n\n#### Formal Justification\nIf MERGE resolves conflicts, then `MERGE(S₁, S₂)` depends on schema — but schema is\nitself data in the store. This creates a circular dependency that breaks L1–L3.\nResolution at query time avoids this: MERGE is always set union, and LIVE applies\nresolution modes.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :element/traces-to :v "C4, ADRS AS-001" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :adr/problem :v "When does conflict resolution happen?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "2d65a55b8f2e3004290fcf60ce3027df5cf11e5c376c2159f598bddf29b1fc03" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option B.** MERGE must be pure set union (C4). Conflict resolution at merge time would make MERGE depend on schema and resolution mode, breaking the algebraic properties (L1–L3 assume set union)." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-003 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :db/doc :v "Conservative Detection Over Precise" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-001\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nShould conflict detection be conservative (may overcount) or precise (exact)?\n\n#### Options\nA) **Conservative** — flag potential conflicts even when uncertain.\n   May waste effort on phantom conflicts. Never misses real conflicts.\nB) **Precise** — only flag actual conflicts. Requires global knowledge.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option A.** The cost of a missed conflict (silent data corruption) far exceeds\nthe cost of a phantom conflict (wasted investigation effort). Conservative detection\nis safe under partial information (local frontiers).\n\n#### Formal Justification\nCausal-ancestor relation is monotonically growing. Learning about new causal paths\ncan only resolve apparent concurrency, never create it. Conservative detection is\nsafe at any frontier.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-001" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :adr/problem :v "Should conflict detection be conservative (may overcount) or precise (exact)?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "f7468d809bc9d3fa641aec996278ff9f6c487415efba2e14a9a1036c83c1143b" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option A.** The cost of a missed conflict (silent data corruption) far exceeds the cost of a phantom conflict (wasted investigation effort). Conservative detection is safe under partial information (local frontiers)." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-004 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :db/doc :v "Three-Tier Routing" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-002\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nHow should conflicts be escalated?\n\n#### Decision\nThree tiers based on severity (commitment weight of conflicting datoms):\n1. **Automatic** (low) — lattice/LWW per attribute. Recorded as datom.\n2. **Agent-with-notification** (medium) — automatic + notification signal.\n3. **Human-required** (high) — blocks. Creates Deliberation entity.\n\nSeverity = `max(commitment_weight(d₁), commitment_weight(d₂))`.\nThresholds configurable as datoms.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-002" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :adr/problem :v "How should conflicts be escalated?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ab797fcd07355f16a5b92ce8f223709b92638a65a21c210d775f1b6d3f7499e5" :a :adr/decision :v "Three tiers based on severity (commitment weight of conflicting datoms): 1. **Automatic** (low) — lattice/LWW per attribute. Recorded as datom. 2. **Agent-with-notification** (medium) — automatic + notification signal. 3. **Human-required** (high) — blocks. Creates Deliberation entity. Severity = `max(commitment_weight(d₁), commitment_weight(d₂))`. Thresholds configurable as datoms." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-005 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :db/doc :v "Deliberation as Entity" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: ADRS CR-004\n**Stage**: 2\n\n#### Problem\nHow to record conflict resolution decisions?\n\n#### Decision\nThree entity types: Deliberation (process), Position (stance), Decision (outcome).\nDeliberation history forms a case law system — past decisions inform future conflicts\nvia the precedent query pattern (CR-007).\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :element/traces-to :v "ADRS CR-004" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :adr/problem :v "How to record conflict resolution decisions?" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "ac34527f795fa18a6837f6db260cc71ee87c3bebdbc6be02983101de95a3d9f6" :a :adr/decision :v "Three entity types: Deliberation (process), Position (stance), Decision (outcome). Deliberation history forms a case law system — past decisions inform future conflicts via the precedent query pattern (CR-007)." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-009 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :db/doc :v "BLAKE3 Hash Tie-Breaking for LWW" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: INV-RESOLUTION-005, ADR-STORE-013, ADRS CR-009\n**Stage**: 0\n\n#### Problem\nWhen two concurrent assertions have identical HLC timestamps for a cardinality-one\nLWW attribute, the resolution is undefined. Without a deterministic tie-breaker, two\nagents resolving the same conflict could pick different winners, violating\nINV-RESOLUTION-002 (commutativity) and breaking CRDT convergence.\n\n#### Options\nA) **BLAKE3 hash of datom content** — compute `blake3([e, a, v, tx, op])` for each\n   competing datom; the datom with the lexicographically greater hash wins. Deterministic,\n   content-addressable, consistent with ADR-STORE-013 (BLAKE3 already used for EntityId).\nB) **Agent ID lexicographic comparison** — break ties by comparing the agent ID embedded\n   in the HLC timestamp. Simple but creates an implicit agent hierarchy: agents with\n   lexicographically later IDs always win ties, incentivizing ID manipulation.\nC) **Leave undefined** — let implementations choose. Breaks CRDT convergence guarantee\n   across heterogeneous implementations.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option A.** BLAKE3 hash comparison provides a deterministic, topology-agnostic total\norder over datoms. Both agents independently compute the same winner without coordination.\nThe hash is already computed for EntityId generation (ADR-STORE-013), so the marginal\ncost is zero for entities and negligible for the full datom tuple.\n\n#### Formal Justification\nThe tie-breaking rule preserves all three CRDT semilattice properties required by\nINV-RESOLUTION-005:\n\n- **Commutativity**: `max(blake3(d₁), blake3(d₂)) = max(blake3(d₂), blake3(d₁))` —\n  byte comparison is commutative under max.\n- **Associativity**: `max(max(h₁, h₂), h₃) = max(h₁, max(h₂, h₃))` — max over a\n  total order is associative.\n- **Idempotency**: `max(h, h) = h` — trivially holds.\n\nBLAKE3's collision resistance (2^{-128} birthday bound) makes hash equality between\ndistinct datoms practically impossible. In the astronomically unlikely event of a\nhash collision, both agents still agree (they compute the same hash), so convergence\nis preserved.\n\n#### Consequences\n- No new dependencies (BLAKE3 already required by ADR-STORE-013)\n- No agent hierarchy — tie-breaking is content-derived, not identity-derived\n- Deterministic across all implementations that use BLAKE3 (the only permitted hash per ADR-STORE-013)\n- The tie-breaking case is rare in practice (requires exact HLC equality, which implies\n  near-simultaneous assertions on different agents with identical logical clock state)" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :element/traces-to :v "INV-RESOLUTION-005, ADR-STORE-013, ADRS CR-009" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :adr/problem :v "When two concurrent assertions have identical HLC timestamps for a cardinality-one LWW attribute, the resolution is undefined. Without a deterministic tie-breaker, two agents resolving the same conflict could pick different winners, violating INV-RESOLUTION-002 (commutativity) and breaking CRDT convergence." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a2890a4ce7b417cf6896f590aa392150a62adea35acd0a88e66c4cbebd3884cc" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option A.** BLAKE3 hash comparison provides a deterministic, topology-agnostic total order over datoms. Both agents independently compute the same winner without coordination. The hash is already computed for EntityId generation (ADR-STORE-013), so the marginal cost is zero for entities and negligible for the full datom tuple." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-006 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :db/doc :v "Delegation Threshold Formula" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: SEED §6, ADRS UA-004\n**Stage**: 2\n\n#### Problem\nHow should the system determine whether a spec element is safe for an agent to work on\nautonomously, or whether it requires consultation, delegation, or human escalation? The\ndelegation decision depends on multiple factors — graph centrality, uncertainty, conflict\nexposure — and needs a principled combination formula.\n\n#### Options\nA) **Single-factor threshold** — delegate based solely on uncertainty level. Simple but\n   ignores structural importance (a low-uncertainty but highly-connected entity is still\n   risky to delegate).\nB) **Multi-factor weighted formula** — combine betweenness centrality, in-degree,\n   consequential uncertainty, and conflict surface into a single threshold score, with\n   weights configurable as datoms.\nC) **Rule-based classification** — a decision tree with hard-coded cutoffs per factor.\n   Interpretable but brittle and not adaptable to different project topologies.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option B.** The delegation threshold is computed as:\n\n```\nthreshold = 0.3 × betweenness + 0.2 × in_degree + 0.3 × σ_c + 0.2 × conflict_surface\n```\n\nwhere `conflict_surface` = fraction of the entity's cardinality-one attributes that are\ncurrently in conflict. The four weights are stored as datoms and configurable per deployment.\n\nThe threshold feeds into a four-class delegation classification (ADR-RESOLUTION-007):\n- `delegatable`: resolvers > 0 AND uncertainty < 0.2\n- `contested`: resolvers > 0 AND uncertainty >= 0.2\n- `escalated`: resolvers = 0 AND uncertainty < 0.5\n- `human-required`: resolvers = 0 AND uncertainty >= 0.5\n\n#### Formal Justification\nThe multi-factor formula captures four independent risk dimensions:\n- **Betweenness** (0.3): structural importance — high-betweenness entities are bottlenecks\n  whose incorrect modification cascades through the dependency graph.\n- **In-degree** (0.2): direct dependence — entities referenced by many others carry higher\n  revision cost.\n- **σ_c** (0.3): consequential uncertainty — entities whose downstream DAG contains high\n  uncertainty are riskier to modify (changes propagate through uncertain territory).\n- **Conflict surface** (0.2): active contention — entities with many cardinality-one\n  attributes in conflict are actively contested and unsafe for unilateral work.\n\nThe weights sum to 1.0 and are stored as datoms (C3: schema-as-data), enabling empirical\ncalibration without code changes. The formula is topology-agnostic (PD-005), depending\nonly on graph metrics computable at any agent's local frontier.\n\n#### Consequences\n- Delegation decisions are reproducible: any agent with the same frontier computes the\n  same threshold for the same entity\n- Weights are empirically tunable — Stage 0 uses defaults; later stages calibrate from\n  observed delegation outcomes (successful autonomous work vs. conflicts discovered post-hoc)\n- The formula degrades gracefully with incomplete frontiers: missing graph data increases\n  uncertainty terms, biasing toward conservative (non-delegation) classification\n\n#### Falsification\nThe formula is wrong if: (1) entities classified as `delegatable` consistently produce\nconflicts when worked on autonomously (threshold too permissive), or (2) entities classified\nas `human-required` are routinely resolved without human intervention (threshold too\nconservative). Calibration should reduce both error modes over time.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :element/traces-to :v "SEED §6, ADRS UA-004" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :adr/problem :v "How should the system determine whether a spec element is safe for an agent to work on autonomously, or whether it requires consultation, delegation, or human escalation? The delegation decision depends on multiple factors — graph centrality, uncertainty, conflict exposure — and needs a principled combination formula." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "5340718129b4b31ecd568933e2830e254b50316d1055a8dc242f54f28715024d" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option B.** The delegation threshold is computed as: ``` threshold = 0.3 × betweenness + 0.2 × in_degree + 0.3 × σ_c + 0.2 × conflict_surface ``` where `conflict_surface` = fraction of the entity's cardinality-one attributes that are currently in conflict. The four weights are stored as datoms and configurable per deployment. The threshold feeds into a four-class delegation classification (ADR-RESOLUTION-007): - `delegatable`: resolvers > 0 AND uncertainty < 0.2 - `contested`: resolvers > 0 AND uncertainty >= 0.2 - `escalated`: resolvers = 0 AND uncertainty < 0.5 - `human-required`: resolvers = 0 AND uncertainty >= 0.5" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-007 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :db/doc :v "Four-Class Delegation" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: SEED §6, ADRS UA-005\n**Stage**: 2\n\n#### Problem\nHow should the system classify work items for agent delegation? A binary delegatable/not\nclassification is too coarse — it conflates \"needs a quick consultation\" with \"requires\nhuman judgment.\"\n\n#### Options\nA) **Binary classification** — delegatable or not. Simple but forces agents to either\n   proceed alone or stop entirely.\nB) **Three classes** — self-handle, delegate, escalate. Missing the intermediate \"consult\"\n   class where an agent can proceed but should check with a peer.\nC) **Four classes** — self-handle, consult, delegate, escalate to human. Provides granular\n   routing that matches the spectrum of uncertainty and authority levels.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option C.** Four delegation classes:\n\n1. **Self-handle** — agent has sufficient authority and the entity is stable. Proceed\n   autonomously. No coordination required.\n2. **Consult** — agent can proceed but should notify a peer agent or check the result.\n   The work is not blocked but a second opinion reduces risk.\n3. **Delegate** — the entity requires a specialist agent (higher authority in the relevant\n   domain per spectral authority UA-003). The current agent should hand off rather than\n   attempt the work.\n4. **Escalate to human** — uncertainty is too high or no agent has sufficient authority.\n   The entity is blocked until a human makes a decision. Creates a Deliberation entity\n   (ADR-RESOLUTION-005).\n\n#### Formal Justification\nThe four classes map to the delegation threshold (ADR-RESOLUTION-006) and the three-tier\nconflict routing (ADR-RESOLUTION-004):\n- Self-handle corresponds to Tier 1 (automatic) — low severity, low uncertainty.\n- Consult corresponds to Tier 2 (agent-with-notification) — medium severity.\n- Delegate routes to the agent with highest spectral authority for the entity's domain.\n- Escalate corresponds to Tier 3 (human-required) — high severity or zero resolvers.\n\nThe classification is topology-agnostic (PD-005): in a hierarchy, \"delegate\" routes upward;\nin a swarm, \"delegate\" routes to the highest-authority peer; in single-agent mode, \"consult\"\ndegrades to self-review and \"delegate\" degrades to \"escalate.\"\n\n#### Consequences\n- Agents have a clear protocol for each class — no ambiguity about when to proceed vs. stop\n- The classification feeds into the harvest delegation topology (ADR-HARVEST-004):\n  self-handle -> self-review, consult -> peer-review, delegate -> specialist, escalate -> human\n- Single-agent deployments collapse to two effective classes: self-handle and escalate\n\n#### Falsification\nThe four classes are wrong if a significant fraction of work items fall into gaps between\nclasses (e.g., too risky for self-handle but not warranting consultation), or if the consult\nclass provides no measurable benefit over binary self-handle/escalate.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :element/traces-to :v "SEED §6, ADRS UA-005" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :adr/problem :v "How should the system classify work items for agent delegation? A binary delegatable/not classification is too coarse — it conflates \"needs a quick consultation\" with \"requires human judgment.\"" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "d24c5aac7d310a60467e15500295668a72c4953b998fb24f4cd7debe13fc6f65" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option C.** Four delegation classes: 1. **Self-handle** — agent has sufficient authority and the entity is stable. Proceed autonomously. No coordination required. 2. **Consult** — agent can proceed but should notify a peer agent or check the result. The work is not blocked but a second opinion reduces risk. 3. **Delegate** — the entity requires a specialist agent (higher authority in the relevant domain per spectral authority UA-003). The current agent should hand off rather than attempt the work. 4. **Escalate to human** — uncertainty is too high or no agent has sufficient authority. The entity is blocked until a human makes a decision. Creates a Deliberation entity (ADR-RESOLUTION-005)." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-008 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :spec/element-type :v :spec.element/adr :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :spec/namespace :v :spec.ns/resolution :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :db/doc :v "Delegation Safety" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :spec/source-file :v "04-resolution.md" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :element/body :v "**Traces to**: SEED §6, ADRS UA-011\n**Stage**: 2\n\n#### Problem\nWhat prevents an agent from beginning work on a spec element that is actively contested\nby concurrent agents? Without a safety check, an agent might implement a function whose\nsignature is being debated in a parallel branch, producing wasted work or conflicting\nartifacts.\n\n#### Options\nA) **Optimistic delegation** — agents proceed freely; conflicts detected and resolved\n   after the fact via the conflict pipeline (§4.2). Simple but wastes effort on contested\n   entities.\nB) **Pessimistic locking** — agents acquire exclusive locks on entities before working.\n   Prevents conflicts but creates contention and deadlock risks.\nC) **Delegation safety predicate** — agents check a delegatability predicate before\n   beginning work. Not a lock — the check is advisory and based on the agent's local\n   frontier. Work on non-delegatable entities is blocked, not prevented by coordination.\n\n#### Decision\n**Option C.** An agent MUST NOT begin work on spec element `e` unless `delegatable(e) = true`\nat the agent's local frontier.\n\n```\ndelegatable(e) =\n  ∀ a ∈ attributes(e): ¬conflict(e, a)     — no active conflicts on any attribute\n  ∧ stability(e) ≥ delegation_threshold      — stability above configured threshold\n```\n\nThis is a local check — no coordination with other agents required. The predicate is\nconservative: it may block work on entities that are actually safe (because the agent's\nfrontier is behind), but it never permits work on entities that are genuinely contested.\n\n#### Formal Justification\nThe safety predicate is conservative by the same argument as INV-RESOLUTION-003 (conservative\nconflict detection): the agent's local frontier may overestimate conflicts (seeing phantom\nconflicts from missing causal paths) but never underestimates them. Therefore:\n\n```\ndelegatable(F_local, e) = true ⟹ delegatable(F_global, e) = true\n```\n\nAn entity that passes the local delegatability check is genuinely safe. An entity that fails\nmay or may not be safe — the agent errs on the side of caution.\n\nThis is NOT a lock. Two agents may independently determine that the same entity is\ndelegatable and begin concurrent work. This is acceptable because their work produces\ndatoms that merge via set union (C4), and any resulting conflicts are detected by the\nconflict pipeline. The safety predicate reduces the frequency of conflicts, not eliminates\nthem.\n\n#### Consequences\n- Agents avoid wasted work on contested entities without requiring a distributed locking\n  protocol\n- The predicate is computable from local state — no network round-trips or coordination\n- False negatives (blocking safe work) decrease as the agent's frontier grows\n- The delegation_threshold is configurable as a datom, enabling per-deployment tuning\n\n#### Falsification\nThe safety predicate is violated if an agent begins implementing a function whose signature\nis contested by concurrent planning agents at the global frontier, and the agent's local\nfrontier contained both conflicting datoms (meaning the predicate should have returned\nfalse but did not). Also violated if the predicate blocks work on entities that are\nconsistently safe, causing unnecessary starvation.\n\n---" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :element/traces-to :v "SEED §6, ADRS UA-011" :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :adr/problem :v "What prevents an agent from beginning work on a spec element that is actively contested by concurrent agents? Without a safety check, an agent might implement a function whose signature is being debated in a parallel branch, producing wasted work or conflicting artifacts." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "75a9cf557183dbb54b3aa83b52fa158f25cc7394e6c381095dfaee3f6eb1b162" :a :adr/decision :v "**Option C.** An agent MUST NOT begin work on spec element `e` unless `delegatable(e) = true` at the agent's local frontier. ``` delegatable(e) = ∀ a ∈ attributes(e): ¬conflict(e, a)     — no active conflicts on any attribute ∧ stability(e) ≥ delegation_threshold      — stability above configured threshold ``` This is a local check — no coordination with other agents required. The predicate is conservative: it may block work on entities that are actually safe (because the agent's frontier is behind), but it never permits work on entities that are genuinely contested." :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "cf56a237412691bf6889d6f0352f3e11dc45aae862ca0cea4831e50d3fdbfb04" :a :db/ident :v :spec/adr-resolution-010 :op :assert}
